The stem Which runs through the ‘middle of the‘ leaf is either beaten down with a bat or removed entirely. The leaves thus prepared are twisted into ropes, by means of a Wheel, and then rolled upon a cylindrical piece of wood. This cylin- der, With its tobacco, is placed under the shade of a roof in such a manner that it may receive the heat of the sun, and yet not be touched by any of its rays. The tobacco, thus compressed spirally upon the cylinder, exudes a black, glu— tinous juice, Which falls drop by drop into a hide placed underneath. This juice flows daily through, and in like manner is daily poured , again upon the folds ; and When the whole mass is thoroughly penetrated by the liquor, it will be necessary to roll the spira] folds daily back again from one cylinder to another. By this method, the lowest part of the tobacco nearest the first cylinder is transferred on the next to the surface, imbibes the juice equally, blackenS, and grows rich like lard. To effect this, the trans- lation from one cylinder to another, and the sprinkling of the tobaCCO, must be diligently continued for many weekS.
